			<p>I found this post via Lifehacker -- which also called out a post from Friday (http://www.lifehacker.com/software/employment/your-extra-interests-can-get-you-a-job-193421.php) that emphasized adding your outside interests to a resume. </p>

<p>Well, which is it? I have to say, I&#39;ve never felt comfortable putting my interests and activities on a resume, although i can see how leadership or volunteer activities that echo one&#39;s professional skills can provide more evidence.</p>

<p>And, after skimming through the comments, I&#39;ll offer my thanks for the inclusive language. I was recently interviewing a very skilled back-up engineer who blurted out, &quot;I was so surprised when I was told a woman would be the hiring manager. I&#39;ve never had a woman manager before.&quot; (She&#39;s ended up at one one of the big names here in the valley.)</p>
